{"title_page": "Thomas Mathews (politician)", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name          = Thomas Mathews\n|image         = Genmathews.jpg\n|office        = 7th [[List of Speakers of the Virginia House of Delegates|Speaker of the Virginia House of Delegates]]\n|vicepresident = \n|term_start    = 1782\n|term_end      = 1793\n|predecessor   = [[Joseph Prentis]]\n|successor     = [[John Wise (Virginia politician)|John Wise]]\n|office1       = \n|appointer1    = \n|term_start1   = \n|term_end1     = \n|predecessor1  = \n|successor1    = \n|birth_date    = c, 1742\n|birth_place   = [[Saint Kitts]], [[West Indies]]\n|death_date    = 1812\n|death_place   = Near [[Norfolk, Virginia]]\n|restingplace  = \n|party         = \n|spouse        = \n|religion      = \n|signature     = \n|signature_alt =\n|allegiance    = {{flagicon|United States of America|1777}} [[United States]]\n|branch        = Virginia provincial militia\n|serviceyears  = Militia: 1776-1783\n|rank          = [[Brigadier General]]\n|commands      = \n|battles       = [[American Revolutionary War]]<br>{{*}}[[Battle of Great Bridge]]<br>{{*}}[[Siege of Yorktown|Battle of Yorktown]]\n|awards        = \n|footnotes     =\n}}\n\n'''Thomas Mathews''' (1742\u20131812) was an [[American people|American]] [[American Revolutionary War|Revolutionary War]] general and [[Virginia]] politician.  He represented [[Norfolk, Virginia|Norfolk Borough]] in the [[Virginia House of Delegates]], and served as that body's [[List of Speakers of the Virginia House of Delegates|Speaker]] from 1782 until 1793.<ref name = Harris>Harris, J.D. (1901) General Thomas Mathews. The Virginia Law Register , Vol. 7, No. 3 (Jul., 1901), pp. 153-158 https://www.jstor.org/stable/1100495 Retrieved October 25, 2013</ref>\n[[File:Dtc.1.jpg|thumb|right|Miniature of Gen. Thomas Mathews]]\nThomas Mathews was born c. 1742 on [[Saint Kitts]], an island of the [[West Indies]]. He was appointed [[brigadier general]] in the Virginia militia in 1776, and led a company to the [[Battle of Great Bridge]], and later to the [[Siege of Yorktown|Battle of Yorktown]]. He was elected to the [[Virginia House of Delegates]] in post-war years and after serving in house for several years was elected its [[List of Speakers of the Virginia House of Delegates|Speaker]] in 1782, remaining as such through the 1793 legislation. He was afterward a candidate for the [[Governors of Virginia|governorship of Virginia]], but he withdrew his nomination.<ref name=\"Harris\"/>\n\nHe was a [[Masonry|mason]], and in 1790 was elected [[Grand Master (Masonic)|Grand Master]] of the [[Grand Lodge of Virginia]]. He served as grand master until 1793, at which point the office was passed to [[John Marshall]].<ref name=\"Harris\"/>\n\n[[Mathews County, Virginia]] was named for him.<ref name=\"Harris\"/> He has been connected to the [[Mathews family|Mathews family]] of Virginia by some historians,<ref name = Harris/><ref name=Lexington>''Lexington Gazette'' (1938). \"Capt. John Mathews and his Descendants.\" 1738\u20131938. Bi-centennial Issue: Commemorating the Settlement of the Rockbridge Section of Virginia by the White Men. A Tribute to the Scotch-Irish Pioneers. Lexington Gazette (Virginia)</ref> though the connection has not been made by others.<ref name=\"WashingtonLee\">Washington and Lee University (1890). ''Historical Papers, Volumes 1\u20132''. New York Public Library: Washington and Lee University, 1890 https://books.google.com/books?id=9p4gAAAAMAAJ&pg=RA1-PA87&dq=%22sampson+mathews%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=8IWVUJiMFqSa0QGKm4GQAQ&ved=0CDoQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=%22sampson%20mathews%22&f=false Retrieved November 3, 2012</ref><ref name=\"Waddell\">Waddell, Joseph A (1902) ''Annals of Augusta County, Virginia, from 1726 to 1871'', [http://www.roanetnhistory.org/waddellsannals.html Waddell's Annals of Augusta County, Virginia, from 1726 to 1871], retrieved October 20, 2012</ref>\n\n\n==See also==\n*[[Saul Matthews]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*[[:File:Vi