l and [[Virginia]] politician.  He represented [[Norfolk, Virginia|Norfolk Borough]] in the [[Virginia House of Delegates]], and served as that body's [[List of Speakers of the Virginia House of Delegates|Speaker]] from 1782 until 1793.<ref name = Harris>Harris, J.D. (1901) General Thomas Mathews. The Virginia Law Register , Vol. 7, No. 3 (Jul., 1901), pp. 153-158 https://www.jstor.org/stable/1100495 Retrieved October 25, 2013</ref>\n[[File:Dtc.1.jpg|thumb|right|Miniature of Gen. Thomas Mathews]]\nThomas Mathews was born c. 1742 on [[Saint Kitts]], an island of the [[West Indies]]. He was appointed [[brigadier general]] in the Virginia militia in 1776, and led a company to the [[Battle of Great Bridge]], and later to the [[Siege of Yorktown|Battle of Yorktown]]. He was elected to the [[Virginia House of Delegates]] in post-war years and after serving in house for several years was elected its [[List of Speakers of the Virginia House of Delegates|Speaker]] in 1782, remaining as such through the 1793 legislation. He was afterward a candidate for the [[Governors of Virginia|governorship of Virginia]], but he withdrew his nomination.<ref name=\"Harris\"/>\n\nHe was a [[Masonry|mason]], and in 1790 was elected [[Grand Master (Masonic)|Grand Master]] of the [[Grand Lodge of Virginia]]. He served as grand master until 1793, at which point the office was passed to [[John Marshall]].<ref name=\"Harris\"/>\n\n[[Mathews County, Virginia]] was named for him.<ref name=\"Harris\"/> He has been connected to the [[Mathews family (Virginia)|Mathews family of Virginia]] by some historians,<ref name = Harris/><ref name=Lexington>''Lexington Gazette'' (1938). \"Capt. John Mathews and his Descendants.\" 1738\u20131938. Bi-centennial Issue: Commemorating the Settlement of the Rockbridge Section of Virginia by the White Men. A Tribute to the Scotch-Irish Pioneers. Lexington Gazette (Virginia)</ref> though the connection has not been made by others.<ref name=\"WashingtonLee\">Washington an